This document specifies the end-to-end onboarding user experience and system behaviour for all authentication types and platform integrations in Foundry IAM. It complements the Platform Specification v1.0, the SAML Extension, SCIM Provisioning, and Custom Federation specs. Every screen state, step sequence, field validation rule, API call, and error condition is defined herein. Engineers and product designers must follow this document as the single source of truth for onboarding implementation.



1  Onboarding Architecture Overview

1.1  Onboarding as a First-Class System Concern

Onboarding is not a marketing concern — it is an engineering surface. Every step in the onboarding funnel makes API calls, creates database records, provisions Keycloak resources, and sends emails. This specification defines those calls with the same rigour as the core platform spec.

Foundry IAM supports four primary onboarding pathways, each corresponding to an authentication protocol. These pathways share a common account creation flow and diverge at the point of credential/integration configuration.



Protocol

Phase

Persona

Trigger

OIDC

MVP — available at launch

Developer / SaaS team

Default for all new signups

SAML 2.0

Phase 2 — post-MVP

Enterprise IT admin

First enterprise deal requiring SAML SSO

SCIM 2.0

Phase 2 — post-MVP

Enterprise IT admin

HR/IdP automated provisioning requirement

Custom Federation

Phase 2 — post-MVP

Enterprise IT admin

Enterprise requiring SSO via existing corporate IdP



1.2  Shared Onboarding Spine

Steps 1–4 are identical across all pathways. Divergence occurs only at Step 5 when the user selects an integration type or begins configuring an application.



#

Step

Actor

System Action

1

Sign Up / Create Account

New user

POST /v1/auth/signup — create Tenant + Workspace + Keycloak realm

2

Email Verification

New user

Keycloak execute-actions-email (VERIFY_EMAIL)

3

Set Password

New user

Keycloak UPDATE_PASSWORD action; sets verified=true on confirmation

4

Intent Survey (4 screens)

New user

Persisted to tenant metadata; drives dashboard personalisation

5

Protocol Configuration ← DIVERGES

User selects pathway

OIDC / SAML / SCIM / Federation branch



1.3  Intent Survey — Screen Sequence & Design Specification

A 4-screen intent survey is the defined pattern for Foundry IAM onboarding. The responses drive dashboard personalisation and inform the Getting Started checklist priority order.



Screen

Question

Options / Field

1 of 4

Priority apps to integrate

Multi-select tiles: Active Directory, Office 365, Google Workspace, Slack, Zoom, Salesforce, AWS IAM, Atlassian Cloud, Dropbox, Datadog, PagerDuty, Other

2 of 4

Where are your users imported from?

Single-select tiles: Active Directory, SuccessFactors, Office 365, CSV/XLS import, Google Workspace, Workday, Other

3 of 4

What features are you most interested in?

Multi-select: Single Sign-On (SSO), Automation & Workflows, Multi-Factor Authentication, Authentication Capabilities, Identity Governance & Administration, Other

4 of 4

What do you want to solve with Foundry IAM?

Free-text textarea — saved to tenant.intent_notes. Max 500 chars.



2  Account Creation & Shared Steps (All Protocols)

2.1  Sign-Up Screen

Route: /signup — Public, unauthenticated



2.1.1  Fields

Field

Type

Validation

Notes

Full Name

text

Required, 2–255 chars

Full Name

text

Required, 2–255 chars

Stored on admins.full_name

Work Email

email

Required, valid email format, domain not blocked

Becomes login credential

Organisation Name

text

Required, 2–255 chars, trimmed

Stored on tenants.name; slug auto-derived

Password

password

Min 12 chars, 1 uppercase, 1 digit, 1 symbol

Never stored in control plane; sent to Keycloak

Confirm Password

password

Must match Password

Client-side validation only

Agree to Terms

checkbox

Must be checked

Terms URL in footer of form



2.1.2  API Calls on Submit

POST /v1/auth/signup

Request body:

full_name, email, organisation_name, password

System actions on success (in order):

1. Validate email not already registered (409 conflict if duplicate)

2. Create tenants record (status=pending)

3. Create workspaces record (mode=shared-realm, status=provisioning)

4. Create Keycloak realm (tnt_<ulid>) — full bootstrap sequence per Platform Spec §5.1

5. Create owner user in Keycloak realm

6. Create admins record (role=owner, status=invited)

7. Trigger Keycloak execute-actions-email: VERIFY_EMAIL

8. Return 201 — redirect to /verify-email



2.1.3  Error States

HTTP

Error Code

User-Facing Message

409

email_already_registered

An account with this email already exists. Sign in instead.

422

password_too_weak

Password must be at least 12 characters and include uppercase, digit, and symbol.

422

domain_blocked

Please use your work email address to create an account.

500

provisioning_failed

We could not create your account. Our team has been notified. Try again in a few minutes.



2.2  Email Verification

Route: /verify-email — Post-signup holding screen

Screen displays: "We sent a verification link to {email}. Click the link to continue." with a Resend Email button (rate-limited: 1 per 60 seconds per email address).

Keycloak handles the verification link. On click, Keycloak marks email_verified=true and redirects to the password-set screen (if password not yet set) or directly to the intent survey.

⚠  Verification links expire after 24 hours. Expired links redirect to /verify-email with error=link_expired.



2.3  Intent Survey Persistence

Survey responses are stored as JSONB on tenants.metadata under the key onboarding_survey. The control plane does not act on these values during MVP but they are available for dashboard personalisation and sales intelligence.

PATCH /v1/tenants/:id — { "metadata": { "onboarding_survey": { "apps": [...], "source": "...", "features": [...], "notes": "..." } } }



2.4  Getting Started Dashboard

Route: /getting-started — First authenticated view after survey completion. Contains a prioritised checklist driven by survey responses. Completion state of each item is tracked and updated as the tenant progresses through setup.



