3.3  OIDC App Management — New App Integration Modal

Route: /apps — "Create a new app integration" modal — sign-in method selection

Sign-in method selection:

OIDC — OpenID Connect: Token-based OAuth 2.0 authentication for SSO through API endpoints. Recommended for custom app integrations. Supports the Foundry IAM Sign-In Widget and direct PKCE flows. [DEFAULT]

SAML 2.0: XML-based open standard for SSO. Use if the Identity Provider for the application only supports SAML.

SWA — Secure Web Authentication: Foundry IAM-specific SSO method. Use if the application does not support OIDC or SAML.

API Services: Interact with Foundry IAM APIs using scoped OAuth 2.0 access tokens for machine-to-machine authentication.

ℹ  SAML 2.0 and API Services selections route to their respective onboarding flows defined in Sections 4 and 7 of this document.



4  SAML 2.0 Onboarding — Enterprise SSO

SAML onboarding is triggered when a user selects "SAML 2.0" from the new app integration modal, or navigates to /saml/new directly. This pathway is gated to Growth and Enterprise plan tenants.

4.1  Pre-Flight Check

⚠  SAML is a Phase 2 feature. Starter plan users who click SAML will see an upgrade prompt. The upgrade CTA links to the billing page.



4.2  SAML Service Provider Registration Flow

Route: /saml/new — Two-tab registration interface



4.2.1  Tab 1 — Upload Metadata (Recommended)

This tab is the default and must be prominently labelled as recommended. Metadata upload is less error-prone than manual configuration.

File upload input — accepts .xml files, max 1MB

Paste textarea — user can paste raw XML directly

On paste or file upload, the system immediately parses the XML client-side:

If valid: extract and display entityId, ACS URL, SLO URL, signing certificate thumbprint in a read-only preview table with a green "Valid Metadata" badge

If invalid XML: red badge with specific error location (line, column)

If valid XML but missing required fields: red badge listing missing fields

ℹ  Required fields in SP metadata: EntityDescriptor entityID, AssertionConsumerService Location, SPSSODescriptor protocolSupportEnumeration.



4.2.2  Tab 2 — Manual Configuration

Field

Required

Type

Notes

SP Entity ID

Yes

text (URL)

Unique identifier of the SP. Usually a URL.

Assertion Consumer Service URL

Yes

text (URL)

HTTPS required in production.

Single Logout URL

No

text (URL)

Leave empty if SP does not support SLO.

NameID Format

Yes

select

Options: Email (default), Persistent, Transient, Unspecified

SP Signing Certificate

No

textarea (PEM)

Paste SP certificate for request signing validation.



4.2.3  Common Fields (Both Tabs)

Field

Required

Notes

Name

Yes

Human label, e.g. "Salesforce Production". Stored as saml_service_providers.name.

Sign Assertions

Yes

Toggle — default ON. Required for all production SPs.

Encrypt Assertions

Yes

Toggle — default OFF. Enable for SPs requiring encrypted assertions.

Attribute Mappings

No

Dynamic table: add/remove rows. Left: Keycloak attribute. Right: SAML attribute name. Format dropdown: Basic / URI.



4.3  SAML Registration API Call

POST /v1/workspaces/:id/saml/service-providers

System actions on success:

1. Validate metadata XML (if upload mode) or manual fields

2. POST /admin/realms/{realm}/clients — create SAML client in Keycloak (protocol=saml)

3. Apply attribute mappers to Keycloak client

4. Persist saml_service_providers record in control plane DB

5. Return 201 with sp details and idp_metadata_url



4.4  SAML Detail Page — Post-Registration

Route: /saml/:id — Immediate destination after successful SP registration



"Give This to Your SP" Section

This section must appear at the top of the page. It contains what the customer must give to their SP to complete the integration.

IdP Metadata URL: {issuer}/protocol/saml/descriptor — copyable + open link

Download IdP Metadata XML button — triggers GET /v1/workspaces/:id/saml/idp-metadata

Signing Certificate download (PEM format) — for SPs that require manual cert upload

EntityID: {issuer} — copyable

SSO URL (POST binding): {issuer}/protocol/saml — copyable

SSO URL (Redirect binding): {issuer}/protocol/saml — copyable



SP-Specific Integration Guides

SP

Key Steps

Salesforce

Setup → Single Sign-On Settings → New → SAML Enabled → paste IdP EntityID, SSO URL, Certificate

Google Workspace

Admin Console → Apps → Web and mobile apps → Add SAML app → upload IdP metadata XML

Azure AD / M365

Azure Portal → Enterprise Applications → New (non-gallery) → Set up single sign-on → SAML → upload metadata XML

ServiceNow

System Properties → SSO → SAML 2.0 → Import IdP metadata XML

Generic SP

Provide IdP metadata XML URL. Configure ACS URL, EntityID, NameID format as shown above.



5  SCIM 2.0 Onboarding — Automated Provisioning

SCIM onboarding is accessed via the workspace sidebar: Settings → SCIM Provisioning. It is gated to Growth and Enterprise plan tenants. The flow enables enterprise customers to connect their HR system or Identity Provider for automated user lifecycle management.

5.1  SCIM Activation Flow

Route: /scim — SCIM Configuration page



5.1.1  Disabled State

Large "Enable SCIM Provisioning" CTA button. One-sentence explainer: "Connect your Identity Provider to automatically create, update, and deactivate users in Foundry IAM." Link to SCIM setup guide.

Plan check: if Starter plan, replace button with upgrade prompt.



5.1.2  Activation Modal — Critical UX

On clicking Enable SCIM Provisioning:

Modal appears: "Your SCIM Bearer Token will only be displayed once. Copy it now and store it securely."

Checkbox: "I understand this token will not be shown again." — must be checked before proceeding.

Confirm button calls POST /v1/workspaces/:id/scim/enable

Response renders the bearer_token in a masked input with copy button and visible eye icon to reveal.

"I have securely stored this token" button closes modal. Once dismissed, the full token is never retrievable.

⚠  The bearer_token is stored as SHA-256 hash in the control plane DB. The raw token is never stored. Token rotation is the only recovery path if the token is lost.



5.1.3  Enabled State — SCIM Config Page

After enabling, the page displays:

Status badge: green "Active" pill

SCIM Base URL: https://api.{domain}/scim/v2/{workspace_id} — copyable

Token: {prefix}... — copyable prefix, "Rotate Token" button

Schemas URL: copyable

ServiceProviderConfig URL: copyable



5.2  SCIM Configuration Settings

Setting

Default

Description

Deprovision Action

Disable

What happens when DELETE is called: Disable (disables KC user, preserves record) or Delete (hard deletes KC user). Warning shown for Delete.

Sync Groups

ON

Whether group membership changes from IdP are applied to Keycloak groups.

Allowed Operations

All

Multi-select: CREATE, UPDATE, DISABLE, DELETE. Restrict if IdP should only create, not delete.

Custom Attribute Mapping

None

JSONB editor — map enterprise SCIM extension fields to Keycloak user attributes.



5.3  IdP Setup Guides

Route: /scim/setup-guide — Step-by-step integration instructions per IdP



IdP

Key Steps

Okta

Admin → Applications → [Your App] → Provisioning → Enable API integration → Enter Base URL and Bearer token → Test connection → Enable Create/Update/Deactivate operations

Azure AD / Entra ID

Enterprise Apps → Provisioning → Automatic → Tenant URL = Base URL → Secret Token = Bearer token → Test connection → Start provisioning

Google Workspace

Admin SDK provisioning → SCIM configuration → endpoint URL → authentication → attribute mapping → enable auto-provisioning

OneLogin

Administration → Provisioning → SCIM connector → Base URL + Bearer token → attribute mapping → enable lifecycle operations

Generic SCIM 2.0

SCIM 2.0 endpoint: {Base URL}/Users, {Base URL}/Groups. Auth: Bearer token. Filters supported: userName eq, externalId eq, emails.value eq.



